WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

03:06.978 --> 03:08.094
Anyone here?

03:16.279 --> 03:17.986
My name is Erwin Griswold.

03:18.532 --> 03:20.364
I am the dean
of this place.

03:21.284 --> 03:23.571
Welcome to Harvard Law School.

03:25.247 --> 03:27.239
Take a moment
to look around you.

03:27.791 --> 03:32.001
In this room, there are Rhodes
and Fulbright scholars,

03:32.087 --> 03:33.703
Phi Beta Kappa members,

03:33.797 --> 03:35.754
student body presidents,

03:35.841 --> 03:38.083
and a Harvard football
team captain.

03:39.845 --> 03:40.845
Together,

03:41.847 --> 03:44.009
you will become lawyers.

03:44.850 --> 03:47.217
This is a privilege
you share.

03:48.186 --> 03:52.351
It is also a responsibility
you accept.

03:54.776 --> 03:55.776
Consider.

03:56.987 --> 04:00.480
What does it mean
to be a Harvard man?

04:01.992 --> 04:05.076
A Harvard man is intelligent,
of course,

04:05.162 --> 04:07.905
but he is also tenacious.

04:07.998 --> 04:11.833
He is a leader devoted
to the rule of law.

04:12.753 --> 04:14.665
He is mindful of his country

04:14.755 --> 04:16.747
loyal to tradition,

04:16.839 --> 04:22.052
and he is respectful
and protective of our institutions.

04:26.850 --> 04:30.434
...shall be computed as of subsection A
of this section applied...

04:30.520 --> 04:32.978
Which one makes me
look more like a Harvard man?

04:36.902 --> 04:40.066
I'm thrilled to report that you look
nothing like a Harvard man.

04:40.155 --> 04:41.755
Seriously?
It's the dean's dinner, Marty.

04:41.782 --> 04:44.343
You know how I am at these things.
I need to make a good impression.

04:44.367 --> 04:47.781
And you will, Kiki. But you've got it wrong.
It's not the dress, it's you.

04:49.206 --> 04:51.368
You haven't touched
your tuna casserole.

04:52.417 --> 04:53.828
Come here, sweetie.

04:53.919 --> 04:55.785
Come on. Here we go.

04:57.172 --> 04:58.879
I've put onions in.
They help, right?

04:59.382 --> 05:00.382
Definitely.

05:02.636 --> 05:04.298
I don't like
either of these.

05:10.310 --> 05:11.642
Okay. Where were we?

05:19.528 --> 05:20.528
Thank you.

05:37.879 --> 05:41.714
Ladies and gentlemen, please join us
in the dining room as dinner is served.

05:41.800 --> 05:44.588
And professors,
please escort the ladies in.

05:46.638 --> 05:47.638
May I?

06:04.030 --> 06:06.613
He said, "Professor,
have you corrected our papers?"

06:06.700 --> 06:08.942
And I said, "Correcting them
will take a lifetime.

06:09.035 --> 06:10.151
"I'm merely grading them."

06:14.457 --> 06:16.494
Esteemed colleagues, ladies,

06:17.377 --> 06:20.211
this is only the sixth year
women have had

06:20.297 --> 06:22.789
the privilege to earn
a Harvard law degree.

06:22.883 --> 06:26.376
This little soiree
is our way of saying welcome.

06:26.469 --> 06:28.677
My wife Harriet and I

06:28.763 --> 06:32.302
are very glad all nine
of you have joined us.

06:36.062 --> 06:38.179
Let us go around the table,

06:38.273 --> 06:42.483
and each of you ladies report
who you are, where you're from

06:42.569 --> 06:47.610
and why you're occupying a place at
Harvard that could have gone to a man.

06:53.038 --> 06:54.119
Yeah.

06:54.205 --> 06:55.205
Well...

06:55.957 --> 06:57.573
Why don't you
get us started, dear?

07:01.546 --> 07:04.914
I'm Hennie Callaghan.
Father's a lawyer back in Minneapolis.

07:05.008 --> 07:07.796
He used to give me drafts of
contracts to use for drawing paper,

07:07.886 --> 07:10.173
but at some point,
I got more interested

07:10.263 --> 07:11.925
in reading them
than drawing on them.

07:13.183 --> 07:17.177
In a few years, it's gonna be
Callaghan and Callaghan.

07:17.270 --> 07:18.852
That was fine.

07:20.065 --> 07:21.065
Next.

07:24.486 --> 07:26.523
Emily Hicks. Hello.

07:26.613 --> 07:27.613
Connecticut.

07:27.697 --> 07:30.986
When I finished Mount Holyoke,
my mother wanted me to get married.

07:31.618 --> 07:32.734
But I didn't wanna do that.

07:32.827 --> 07:35.365
And I didn't wanna be
a teacher or a nurse.

07:35.455 --> 07:36.571
- So...
- Ah!

07:37.332 --> 07:39.289
That's not
a very good reason.

07:40.502 --> 07:41.502
Next.

07:46.299 --> 07:47.415
Oh.

07:47.509 --> 07:49.171
- Watch it.
- Sorry.

07:56.393 --> 07:57.393
Uh...

07:57.894 --> 08:01.979
I'm Ruth Ginsburg
from Brooklyn.

08:04.067 --> 08:05.979
And why are you here,
Miss Ginsburg?

08:06.569 --> 08:09.562
Uh, Mrs. Ginsburg, actually.

08:10.407 --> 08:12.615
My husband Marty
is in the second-year class.

08:14.244 --> 08:17.032
I'm at Harvard to learn
more about his work,

08:17.122 --> 08:20.160
so I can be a more patient
and understanding wife.

08:25.005 --> 08:29.124
Come to dinner. The beans will be boiled,
the chicken will be stewed

08:29.217 --> 08:30.549
and you will be grilled.

08:30.635 --> 08:33.342
We came to Harvard
to be lawyers. Why else?

08:33.429 --> 08:34.671
It's truly
an asinine question.

08:34.764 --> 08:36.255
He's never gonna
take me seriously.

08:36.349 --> 08:38.841
No, that's not true.
You're the smartest person here.

08:38.934 --> 08:40.597
And you're gonna be
the most prepared.

08:40.687 --> 08:42.303
So just stand up
and say what you know.

08:42.397 --> 08:44.041
At a place like this,
that's all that matters.

08:44.065 --> 08:48.105
In my experience, even small mistakes
are glaring when you stick out.

08:49.487 --> 08:51.604
Well, then you're very lucky.

08:53.450 --> 08:54.450
Because you

08:56.828 --> 08:59.195
are very short.

09:11.134 --> 09:12.134
Oh, yeah?

09:18.349 --> 09:19.385
Yeah.

09:21.478 --> 09:27.725
Well, why don't you come down
here and say that to my face?

09:53.051 --> 09:54.758
Mrs. Ginsburg.

09:54.844 --> 09:55.844
Hmm.

10:12.904 --> 10:17.740
I am Professor Brown.
This is Introduction to Contracts.

10:17.992 --> 10:20.200
<i>Hawkins v. McGee.</i>

10:21.329 --> 10:23.787
State the case, please.

10:33.508 --> 10:34.508
Mr. Pruitt.

10:37.053 --> 10:39.716
Uh, good morning. I'm Donald Pruitt.
I'm really honored to be here.

10:39.806 --> 10:41.297
<i>Hawkins v. McGee.</i>

10:41.391 --> 10:42.882
Uh, yeah,
<i>Hawkins v. McGee,</i>

10:42.976 --> 10:45.764
it's a fascinating breach
of contract case where...

10:46.896 --> 10:48.888
Charles Hawkins hurt
his hand and McGee...

10:48.982 --> 10:50.564
Can someone help him please?

10:59.450 --> 11:00.782
Mr. Fitzpatrick.

11:03.413 --> 11:06.121
It was Charles' son who hurt his hand.
Electrocution burn.

11:06.207 --> 11:08.870
And at what point does the case turn,
Mr. Fitzpatrick?

11:09.627 --> 11:12.995
McGee promised to fix the hand
by performing a skin graft.

11:13.089 --> 11:15.126
But McGee wasn't very familiar
with the procedure

11:15.216 --> 11:17.208
and the results weren't
quite what he planned.

11:20.263 --> 11:23.552
Question already?
Mrs. Ginsburg.

11:23.641 --> 11:24.927
Correction, Professor Brown.

11:25.018 --> 11:28.261
McGee did not simply promise
to fix George Hawkins' hand,

11:28.354 --> 11:29.686
he promised, quote,

11:30.398 --> 11:32.481
"a 100% good hand."

11:32.567 --> 11:33.728
That's the same thing.

11:33.818 --> 11:34.818
Is it?

11:35.153 --> 11:36.735
What say you, Mrs. Ginsburg?

11:36.905 --> 11:37.986
It is not.

11:38.740 --> 11:40.026
Words matter.

11:40.658 --> 11:43.150
McGee grafted skin
from Hawkins' chest.

11:43.244 --> 11:45.236
Not only did this fail
to fix the scarring,

11:45.330 --> 11:47.367
he had chest hair
growing on his palm.

11:47.457 --> 11:49.824
Proving that a hand
with a burn is worth two with a bush.

11:52.962 --> 11:54.749
The court denied
Hawkins damages.

11:54.839 --> 11:56.150
Hawkins did get damages.
The court said...

11:56.174 --> 11:57.506
If I may finish?

11:58.843 --> 12:01.836
Hawkins was denied damages
for pain and suffering.

12:02.096 --> 12:05.089
The New Hampshire Supreme Court
ruled he was entitled to damages

12:05.183 --> 12:07.891
only based on the contract
being fulfilled.

12:09.812 --> 12:12.179
So if Dr. McGee had set
realistic expectations

12:12.273 --> 12:14.014
instead of making
grand promises,

12:14.108 --> 12:16.350
Hawkins' award
likely would have been less.

12:20.657 --> 12:23.946
Was that an answer,
Mrs. Ginsburg, or a filibuster?

12:30.041 --> 12:31.041
Hmm.

12:36.422 --> 12:37.503
Movie.

12:38.007 --> 12:39.007
Four words.

12:39.259 --> 12:41.171
- Second word.
- Seven?

12:41.261 --> 12:42.297
- Seven.
- Uh-oh.

12:42.387 --> 12:43.387
Fourth word.

12:45.390 --> 12:46.756
- Monkey.
- Oh, gorilla.

12:46.849 --> 12:48.340
Monkey business! Ape!

12:48.434 --> 12:50.300
- Monkey, monkey.
- Ape!

12:51.354 --> 12:52.936
Monkey on my back?

12:55.358 --> 12:56.769
Second word, "seven."

12:56.859 --> 12:58.816
- Seven...
<i>- Seven Brides for Seven Brothers?</i>

12:58.903 --> 13:00.863
- What does that have to do with monkeys?
- And...

13:00.947 --> 13:02.813
- Oh, oh! <i>The Seven Year Itch.</i>
- Time!

13:02.907 --> 13:04.739
Oh! Oh!

13:07.370 --> 13:09.532
Ruthless Ruthy
strikes again.

13:09.622 --> 13:11.534
Okay. Next round's
riding on you.

13:12.000 --> 13:13.491
Don't worry,
he's very good.

13:13.584 --> 13:15.604
Thank God, because she
actually broke up with someone

13:15.628 --> 13:16.668
for being bad at Charades.

13:16.713 --> 13:19.626
- You didn't really?
- It was a manifestation

13:19.716 --> 13:20.877
of his being an idiot.

13:20.967 --> 13:22.048
See?

13:22.135 --> 13:23.862
Don't worry, I'm comfortable
being smarter than you.

13:23.886 --> 13:24.886
Oh, thank you.

13:24.971 --> 13:26.291
All right, everybody ready?

13:27.098 --> 13:28.305
Uh, song.

13:30.560 --> 13:32.426
- Buddy Holly?
- Bill Haley.

13:32.854 --> 13:33.890
By Elvis.

13:34.689 --> 13:35.896
Three words.

13:36.274 --> 13:37.714
- First word.
- First word.

13:38.401 --> 13:39.437
Uh...

13:39.527 --> 13:41.063
- Uh, table.
- A glass?

13:41.154 --> 13:42.235
A book.

13:42.322 --> 13:44.154
- Reading!
- Uh, blue!

13:44.240 --> 13:46.698
- Uh, <i>Blueberry Hill.</i>
- No, that's Fats Domino.

13:46.784 --> 13:47.991
- Third word.
- Third word.

13:48.077 --> 13:49.193
- Floor.
- Carpet.

13:49.287 --> 13:51.279
- Dancing?
- Nice moves.

13:53.082 --> 13:54.414
Oh, no sound effects.

13:54.959 --> 13:56.166
Oh, <i>Blue Suede Shoes!</i>

13:56.252 --> 13:58.209
Come on, Marty,
you're a lightweight.

13:58.296 --> 13:59.832
Marty?

13:59.922 --> 14:01.914
Marty?

14:02.008 --> 14:03.749
- Help! Help!
- Is he all right?

14:03.843 --> 14:04.924
Someone get some help!

14:13.061 --> 14:14.597
The doctor's ready
to see you.

14:45.051 --> 14:46.212
Excuse me.

14:46.677 --> 14:47.838
Just a moment please.

14:51.682 --> 14:54.140
- Excuse me, I just...
- Just a moment, I need to make a call.

14:56.354 --> 14:59.062
Yes. Can we have
the results today?

14:59.399 --> 15:00.685
Excuse me?

15:01.234 --> 15:04.102
Doctor. You examined
my husband.

15:04.195 --> 15:06.215
I'm wondering when you think
he'll be able to leave.

15:06.239 --> 15:08.777
- I need to call the sitter...
- What's the patient's name?

15:09.575 --> 15:11.441
Martin Ginsburg.

15:11.536 --> 15:13.323
Right. Ginsburg.

15:13.413 --> 15:15.575
Hmm.

15:15.665 --> 15:16.906
Yeah, he's not
going home today.

15:16.999 --> 15:19.241
- Excuse me?
- We have more tests to run.

15:21.379 --> 15:22.460
What kind of tests?

15:22.547 --> 15:24.191
Various kinds.
He's gonna be with us a while.

15:24.215 --> 15:25.922
What tests?
I need to see him.

15:26.008 --> 15:29.968
Go home, get some rest.
We'll know more in a few days.

15:30.054 --> 15:31.465
Now, if you'll excuse me.

15:36.686 --> 15:37.686
<i>How is he?</i>

15:39.021 --> 15:40.137
Fine.

15:50.032 --> 15:51.739
Call any time, okay?

15:56.122 --> 15:57.158
Bye.

16:48.758 --> 16:50.590
- Hi.
- Hi.

16:57.058 --> 16:59.345
At least you got
a break from my cooking.

17:04.397 --> 17:05.638
Afternoon.

17:05.733 --> 17:07.690
- Hey, Doc.
- Dr. Leadbetter.

17:11.656 --> 17:12.692
It's as we feared.

17:14.742 --> 17:17.108
Marty, you're young,
and we caught it early.

17:18.037 --> 17:20.404
We've pioneered
a new treatment here.

17:20.498 --> 17:25.084
It entails numerous surgeries,
each followed by a course of radiation.

17:25.586 --> 17:29.045
There's a chance you can go on
to a healthy, happy life.

17:29.131 --> 17:30.497
As if none of this
had happened.

17:30.591 --> 17:33.379
Well, what kind of a chance?

17:34.053 --> 17:36.545
Dr. Leadbetter, we'd rather
know what we're facing.

17:39.392 --> 17:42.601
Survival rate for testicular
cancer has been about 5%.

17:46.065 --> 17:47.351
Thanks for the honesty.

17:48.442 --> 17:49.442
I think.

17:49.527 --> 17:50.893
I'll let you two talk.

18:31.986 --> 18:33.397
We're never giving up.

18:35.114 --> 18:36.321
You keep working.

18:38.242 --> 18:39.449
Keep studying.

18:40.077 --> 18:41.909
Jane will have her father.

18:43.748 --> 18:45.239
You will be a lawyer.

18:47.960 --> 18:50.873
I'm spending my life with you,
Martin Ginsburg.

19:13.736 --> 19:15.693
<i>Judicial consistency.</i>

19:16.280 --> 19:21.241
<i>The doctrine of stare decisis
comes from English common law,</i>

19:21.327 --> 19:23.785
which also provides
the first examples

19:23.871 --> 19:27.285
of circumstances where
precedence may be overturned.

19:27.375 --> 19:28.491
Excuse me.

19:29.293 --> 19:31.660
- Judges are bound...
- Thank you.

19:31.754 --> 19:32.961
Excuse me.

19:33.047 --> 19:34.583
May I help you?

19:34.924 --> 19:38.042
Um...
I'm Martin Ginsburg's wife.

19:38.135 --> 19:40.718
I'll be attending
his classes for him.

19:41.764 --> 19:43.471
In addition to your own?

19:44.141 --> 19:46.849
Yes, Professor Freund.

19:53.109 --> 19:57.149
Judges are bound
by precedence,

19:57.238 --> 19:59.400
but they cannot ignore
cultural change.

20:00.241 --> 20:03.780
A court ought not be affected
by the weather of the day,

20:03.869 --> 20:06.987
but will be by
the climate of the era.

20:10.042 --> 20:12.785
<i>Wait, wait, wait.
Say that last part again?</i>

20:13.087 --> 20:17.502
"A court ought not be affected
by the weather of the day,

20:17.591 --> 20:20.584
"but will be by
the climate of the era."

20:24.473 --> 20:25.714
You're sure he said that?

20:29.186 --> 20:30.267
Of course.

20:30.730 --> 20:32.346
Of course.

20:36.902 --> 20:38.814
The law is never finished.

20:40.281 --> 20:42.364
It is a work in progress,

20:45.619 --> 20:47.531
and ever will be.

20:47.621 --> 20:50.113
<i>Brown v. the Board of Education,</i>

20:50.958 --> 20:53.120
parentheses, 1954,

20:53.419 --> 20:55.331
was the most revolutionary

20:56.672 --> 20:58.254
Supreme Court case

20:59.717 --> 21:01.128
in the last century.

21:04.388 --> 21:06.505
Representing Oliver Brown

21:07.850 --> 21:08.850
et al.,

21:09.810 --> 21:11.051
Thurgood Marshall...

21:11.145 --> 21:13.558
- I'm not listening.
- ...educated the court...

21:27.620 --> 21:28.827
Come on, Jane.

21:28.913 --> 21:30.825
That's it, come on, sweetie.

21:46.680 --> 21:47.761
Okay...

23:04.216 --> 23:05.832
<i>One, two, three...</i>

23:06.010 --> 23:07.592
Whoo!

23:07.678 --> 23:09.761
- One, two, three...
- One, two, three...

23:09.847 --> 23:11.032
Whoo!

23:11.056 --> 23:12.467
Should we give
Daddy a rest?

23:13.893 --> 23:16.306
Some day, this little angel's
gonna slam the door in our face

23:16.395 --> 23:18.352
and tell us that
we're ruining her life.

23:21.150 --> 23:22.812
I should've never
taken the job.

23:23.402 --> 23:24.768
It's a great firm.

23:25.112 --> 23:27.900
And New York is the center
of the legal universe.

23:28.741 --> 23:29.902
You earned it.

23:30.784 --> 23:32.150
You earned it.

23:32.244 --> 23:33.985
I barely survived it.

23:35.706 --> 23:37.914
I just don't wanna be away
from you and Jane.

23:38.375 --> 23:39.491
You won't be.

23:40.669 --> 23:41.830
I won't allow it.

23:42.880 --> 23:44.121
I'll convince him.

23:47.092 --> 23:49.254
- Say, "Good luck, Mommy."
- Good luck, Mommy.

23:50.137 --> 23:52.254
<i>You want
a Harvard law degree,</i>

23:52.348 --> 23:55.591
<i>though you plan to finish
your coursework at Columbia?</i>

23:56.977 --> 23:59.515
You would do well,
Mrs. Ginsburg,

23:59.605 --> 24:02.268
to remember how fortunate
you are to be here.

24:02.942 --> 24:04.228
Dean Griswold,

24:04.318 --> 24:07.186
between the first
and third year of law school,

24:07.488 --> 24:10.231
which is the more substantive,
the more critical?

24:10.407 --> 24:11.818
The first, of course.

24:11.909 --> 24:14.777
Yet when someone transfers in
as a second year student

24:14.870 --> 24:18.284
having taken those more important classes
elsewhere, he's allowed a degree.

24:18.415 --> 24:20.577
- That's irrelevant.
- I've been here two years.

24:20.751 --> 24:22.242
I'm first in my class.

24:22.419 --> 24:25.912
There is no reason your
husband cannot provide for you

24:26.006 --> 24:28.623
while you and the child
remain in Cambridge.

24:29.218 --> 24:32.962
Last year, John Sumner was allowed to
finish his course work at Baltimore.

24:33.389 --> 24:35.005
Three years ago,
Roy Paxton...

24:35.099 --> 24:37.056
- Very different cases.
- How are they different?

24:37.142 --> 24:40.431
Mrs. Ginsburg, you have no
compelling need to transfer.

24:44.650 --> 24:46.016
Marty could relapse.

24:48.237 --> 24:49.478
He beat the odds,

24:49.822 --> 24:52.235
but the doctors say
it could happen at any time.

24:56.996 --> 24:58.328
Dean Griswold,

25:00.124 --> 25:01.706
this is my family.

25:04.503 --> 25:05.835
Nonetheless,

25:06.922 --> 25:09.335
we each have
our responsibilities,

25:09.800 --> 25:13.714
and mine is to protect the
distinction of a Harvard law degree.

25:14.471 --> 25:16.463
I can't force you to stay,

25:18.392 --> 25:21.100
but I won't reward you
for leaving, either.

26:35.302 --> 26:37.089
Jesus, Mary, and Joseph.

26:37.971 --> 26:40.554
Graduating top of your class,
law review at Harvard

26:40.849 --> 26:42.090
and Columbia.

26:42.726 --> 26:44.217
I didn't even know
that was possible.

26:44.311 --> 26:45.893
Thank you, Mr. Greene.

26:46.271 --> 26:47.478
I've worked hard.

26:47.731 --> 26:49.688
Well, you'd want some
white-shoe firm.

26:49.775 --> 26:52.267
Big money cases,
complex legal maneuvers...

26:52.361 --> 26:55.354
No, I think Bibler and Greene
is the perfect fit.

26:55.906 --> 26:58.114
You handled the Mercer
bankruptcy last year...

26:58.200 --> 27:00.112
Come on. How many
have you been to?

27:00.702 --> 27:02.694
They all turned you down,
right? How many?

27:03.997 --> 27:05.158
Like 10?

27:07.167 --> 27:08.499
Twelve.

27:08.585 --> 27:11.043
A woman, a mother
and a Jew to boot.

27:12.256 --> 27:14.543
I'm surprised that many
let you through the door.

27:14.633 --> 27:16.966
One sent me to interview
for the secretarial pool.

27:18.137 --> 27:21.380
Another told me I'd be too busy
at bake sales to be effective.

27:21.807 --> 27:24.424
