38:02.155 --> 38:04.175
You know, young people in Sweden
these days aren't getting married?

38:04.199 --> 38:05.406
Really?

38:05.492 --> 38:07.825
- It's true. They're getting engaged.
- Hmm.

38:08.578 --> 38:10.114
They're still
living together.

38:10.747 --> 38:12.488
Still having kids,
raising a family,

38:12.582 --> 38:14.539
but they're not getting married.
You know why?

38:14.626 --> 38:16.066
They can
have sex without it.

38:18.922 --> 38:20.379
It's because of taxes.

38:22.258 --> 38:24.170
It's true. After the war,
Sweden passed a law

38:24.260 --> 38:27.549
that said married couples will
now file joint income tax returns.

38:27.639 --> 38:29.221
However, unlike
the United States,

38:29.307 --> 38:31.147
they weren't given
any of the benefits from it.

38:31.392 --> 38:35.056
So, married Swedes were finding
themselves in the uncomfortable position

38:35.146 --> 38:37.183
of now being in
a higher tax bracket.

38:37.357 --> 38:39.557
- Really?
- So they got divorced.

38:39.984 --> 38:41.664
Of course, they were
still living together.

38:41.694 --> 38:44.186
So the Swedish government
then passes a new law that says,

38:44.280 --> 38:46.146
"All right. Married couples
who get divorced

38:46.241 --> 38:48.699
"but continue to live together
for tax purposes

38:48.785 --> 38:50.617
"will be considered
still married."

38:50.703 --> 38:51.983
So they did what
anyone would do.

38:52.038 --> 38:53.620
They add a second entrance
to their home

38:53.706 --> 38:56.289
with a nice wall that goes
right down the middle

38:56.376 --> 38:58.083
with doors for
easy access.

38:58.211 --> 39:02.330
"All right, fine," says the Swedish government, "new law.

39:02.799 --> 39:06.964
"Once married, now divorced
couples living in a two-income household

39:07.053 --> 39:11.047
